entry.title: [TestTraceProcessor] A workaround for PartitionAllocator crashes
entry.content:
Chrome uses a custom memory allocator in non-component builds that

manages all allocations on the heap. Since test_trace_processor is a

separate library even in a non-component build, Chrome is not able to

free memory allocated by the code in this library. This leads to

crashes when e.g. vectors created here are passed to the code in

Chrome tests.



This CL introduces a custom class to hold the result of the query

execution. Since its destructor is defined in this library, it will

be freed using the same allocator that was used to create it.



Bug: 1453617

entry.title: Fix setting AutofillField::autofill_source_profile_guid_.
entry.content:
autofill_source_profile_guid_ indicates which profile was used to

autofill a field. Right now, its value is even set during preview. This

breaks the assumption that autofill_source_profile_guid_ being set

implies `is_autofilled || previously_autofilled()`.



This hasn't caused any problems, since the source guid is unused. But

it will be used in the implementation of profile token quality.



It seems like is_autofilled had the same bug of being set during

preview in the past. This was fixed with

kAutofillOnlyCacheIsAutofilledOnFill, which is currently rolling out.

This CL moves setting the source guid into the same if. As the source

guid is currently unused, this doesn't affect the ongoing experiment.

entry.title: [iOS] dealloc checks that SceneController was tearDown
entry.content:
Current dealloc only checks that UI is not enabled; which technically

could hold if the UI was never initialized. The SceneController can

hold many object that must be stopped even when UI is not initialized.

So its more relevant to check that `_sceneURLLoadingService` is nil;

as its set in init.



It should be noted that `teardownUI` normally could only be called

after some change of state; so calling it the normal way in test would require to simulate the whole life cycle. In this case, it seems more

reasonable to just call it directly and indicate that it should only

be used for tests.



Executing this method is usually acceptable, given that call on nil

objects are ignored in objective-C. So we just had to add a little

precaution around methods called on c++ object, to avoid

nullptrexception.

entry.title: Revert "[Re-land][Browsing Data Model][site data] Report storage accesses to BDM"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 4e8da3bf29612912556b4d37c35fbf6a974d164b.



Reason for revert:

LUCI Bisection identified this CL as the culprit of a build failure. See the analysis: https://luci-bisection.appspot.com/analysis/b/8776577951028890945



Sample failed build: https://ci.chromium.org/b/8776577951028890945



If this is a false positive, please report it at https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/entry?comment=Analysis%3A+https%3A%2F%2Fluci-bisection.appspot.com%2Fanalysis%2Fb%2F8776577951028890945&components=Tools%3ETest%3EFindit&labels=LUCI-Bisection-Wrong%2CPri-3%2CType-Bug&status=Available&summary=Wrongly+blamed+https%3A%2F%2Fchromium-review.googlesource.com%2Fc%2Fchromium%2Fsrc%2F%2B%2F4608424



Original change's description:

> [Re-land][Browsing Data Model][site data] Report storage accesses to BDM

>

> This is a re-land change. There were some tests failing on crrev.com/c/4608424 due to 1p/3p context lost as we were recording metrics for storage access.

> It was wrong to assume that the context could be derived solely from the storage key and in this updated re-land change I've reverted this line to use the passed argument of `top_frame_origin`.

>

> In this CL:

> - Introduced `SessionStorage` type to BDM for access reports.

> - Moved storage handling under the new feature `kMigrateStorageToBDM`.

> - Updated storage access report to use `blink::StorageKey` instead of

> `GURL` to maintain 3p context and support storage partitioning.

> - Exposed storage_key() method to the RenderFrameHost public interface.

> - Reported access for storage types (i.e. local storage, session storage

> and quota managed storage) to BDM in site data.

> - Added browser tests for all new access reports in BDM.

> - WebSQL is covered in access reports and its browser test relating to

> Quota Managed data.

> - Added a test suite in PSCS unit tests for BDM

> `OnBrowsingDataAccessed` to cover storage access reports.

>

entry.title: [Re-land][Browsing Data Model][site data] Report storage accesses to BDM
entry.content:
This is a re-land change. There were some tests failing on crrev.com/c/4608424 due to 1p/3p context lost as we were recording metrics for storage access.

It was wrong to assume that the context could be derived solely from the storage key and in this updated re-land change I've reverted this line to use the passed argument of `top_frame_origin`.



In this CL:

- Introduced `SessionStorage` type to BDM for access reports.

- Moved storage handling under the new feature `kMigrateStorageToBDM`.

- Updated storage access report to use `blink::StorageKey` instead of

`GURL` to maintain 3p context and support storage partitioning.

- Exposed storage_key() method to the RenderFrameHost public interface.

- Reported access for storage types (i.e. local storage, session storage

and quota managed storage) to BDM in site data.

- Added browser tests for all new access reports in BDM.

- WebSQL is covered in access reports and its browser test relating to

Quota Managed data.

- Added a test suite in PSCS unit tests for BDM

`OnBrowsingDataAccessed` to cover storage access reports.

entry.title: blink/public: Split WebPrivatePtr in GCed and RefCounted pointer
entry.content:
Split the implementation of WebPrivatePtr into WebPrivatePtrForGC and

WebPrivatePtrForRefcounted.



WebPrivatePtrForRefCounted: Same as WebPrivatePtr for

base::scoped_refptr only. Still requires using untyped storage as the

destruction behavior should avoid executing destructors of the

ref-counted types.



WebPrivatePtrForGC: Can directly use the Blink handle as ctor/dtor are

safe to be used with forward declared types and no destructors are

invoked. Using the handle directly has the benefits:

a. PersistentLocation is now available for all such references, making

it much easier to find leaks for debugging.

b. The GC plugin can find (see ignore annotation) roots that are

introduced on the managed object graph. This is a source of leaks and

bloat.



Undo the restrictions from https://crrev.com/c/4637546. Constructors

may now be defined in header files again. This simplifies the usage of

the pointers.
